Durban - A 28-year-old man, arrested for the murder of a tuck shop owner at the Glebelands Hostel in 2017, is due to be sentenced in the Durban Regional Court on Tuesday. 

Khayelihle Mroza Mbuthuma was found guilty of killing Sbongile Mtshali, 25, in July last year. ADVERTISINGinRead invented by Teads

Lieutenant Colonel Thulani Zwane, police spokesperson, said Mtshali was running a tuck shop at her room at the hostel, when she was approached by two men. 

“They pretended to be customers. The suspects opened fire, fatally wounding Mtshali before fleeing the crime scene on foot. She sustained gunshot wounds to the head and chest  and was declared dead at the scene,” he said. 

Mbuthuma was arrested following an intelligence driven operation at the hostel in August. 

In a separate incident at Glebelands, seven men were arrested during early morning raids at the hostel last year. 

Khayelihle Mbuthuma, Eugene Wonderboy Hlophe, policeman Bhekukwazi Louis Mdweshu, Ncomecile Matlala Ntshangase, Mbuyiselwa Mahliphiza Mkhize, Vukani Mcobothi,and Mondli Talente Mthethwa are charged with 17 counts of conspiracy to commit murder, attempted murder, murder and being in possession of ammunition and firearms. Their bail application is ongoing. 

